# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apache-accumulo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apache-accumulo/accumulo-apache-org] With Apache Accumulo, users can store and manage large data sets across a cluster.
[src:apache-accumulo/accumulo-apache-org] Accumulo uses Apache Hadoop's HDFS to store its data and Apache ZooKeeper for consensus.
[src:apache-accumulo/accumulo-apache-org] While many users interact directly with Accumulo, several open source projects use Accumulo as their underlying store.
[src:apache-accumulo/accumulo-apache-org] To learn more about Accumulo, take the Accumulo tour, read the user manual and run the Accumulo example code.
[src:apache-accumulo/accumulo-apache-org] Feel free to contact us if you have any questions.
[src:apache-accumulo/accumulo-apache-org] Major Features Server-side programming Accumulo has a programming mechanism (called Iterators) that can modify key/value pairs at various points in the data management process.
[src:apache-accumulo/accumulo-apache-org] Cell-based access control Every Accumulo key/value pair has its own security label which limits query results based off user authorizations.
[src:apache-accumulo/accumulo-apache-org] Designed to scale Accumulo runs on a cluster using one or more HDFS instances.
[src:apache-accumulo/accumulo-apache-org] Nodes can be added or removed as the amount of data stored in Accumulo changes.
[src:apache-accumulo/accumulo-apache-org] Stable Accumulo has a stable client API that follows LTM releases and semantic versioning.
[src:apache-accumulo/accumulo-apache-org] Each Accumulo release goes through extensive testing.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] Accumulo was created in 2008 by the US National Security Agency and contributed to the Apache Foundation as an incubator project in September 2011.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] On March 21, 2012, Accumulo graduated from incubation at Apache, making it a top-level project.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] In June 2012, the US Senate Armed Services Committee (SASC) released the Draft 2012 Department of Defense (DoD) Authorization Bill, which included references to Apache Accumulo.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] In the draft bill SASC required DoD to evaluate whether Apache Accumulo could achieve commercial viability before implementing it throughout DoD.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] Specific criteria were not included in the draft language, but the establishment of commercial entities supporting Apache Accumulo could be considered a success factor.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] Apache Accumulo extends the Bigtable data model, adding a new element to the key called Column Visibility.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] This element stores a logical combination of security labels that must be satisfied at query time in order for the key and value to be returned as part of a user request.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] This allows data of varying security requirements to be stored in the same table, and allows users to see only those keys and values for which they are authorized.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] In addition to Cell-Level Security, Apache Accumulo provides a server-side programming mechanism called Iterators that allows users to perform additional processing at the Tablet Server.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] The range of operations that can be applied is equivalent to those that can be implemented within a MapReduce Combiner function, which produces an aggregate value for several key-value pairs.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] Apache Accumulo orders entries in order of user keys, and exposes an iterator over a key range.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-accumulo] This allows locality of reference not available from some other distributed stores (including Cassandra and Voldemort that order by hash of the user key).
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The core of Apache Hadoop consists of a storage part, known as Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), and a processing part which is a MapReduce programming model.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Hadoop splits files into large blocks and distributes them across nodes in a cluster.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] It then transfers packaged code into nodes to process the data in parallel.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] This approach takes advantage of data locality, where nodes manipulate the data they have access to.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] This allows the dataset to be processed faster and more efficiently than it would be in a more conventional supercomputer architecture that relies on a parallel file system where computation and data are distributed via high-speed networking.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Apache Hadoop's MapReduce and HDFS components were inspired by Google papers on MapReduce and Google File System.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop framework itself is mostly written in the Java programming language, with some native code in C and command line utilities written as shell scripts.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Perl language can be easily used with Hadoop Streaming to implement the map and reduce parts of the user's program.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] According to its co-founders, Doug Cutting and Mike Cafarella, the idea of Hadoop was conceived in the Google File System paper that was published in October 2003.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The concept was extended in the Google paper *"MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters".* Development started on the Apache Nutch project, but was moved to the new Hadoop subproject in January 2006.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Doug Cutting, who was working at Yahoo! at the time, named it after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The initial code that was factored out of Nutch consisted of about 5,000 lines of code for HDFS and about 6,000 lines of code for MapReduce.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] In March 2006, Owen O'Malley was the first committer to add to the Hadoop project; Hadoop 0.1.0 was released in April 2006.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] It continues to evolve through contributions that are being made to the project.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The first design document for the Hadoop Distributed File System was written by Dhruba Borthakur in 2007.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Hadoop consists of the *Hadoop Common* package, which provides file system and operating system level abstractions, a MapReduce engine (either MapReduce/MR1 or YARN/MR2) and the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop Common package contains the Java Archive (JAR) files and scripts needed to start Hadoop.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] For effective scheduling of work, every Hadoop-compatible file system should provide location awareness, which is the name of the rack, specifically the network switch where a worker node is.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Hadoop applications can use this information to execute code on the node where the data is, and, failing that, on the same rack/switch to reduce backbone traffic.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] HDFS uses this method when replicating data for data redundancy across multiple racks.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] This approach reduces the impact of a rack power outage or switch failure; if any of these hardware failures occurs, the data will remain available.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] A small Hadoop cluster includes a single master and multiple worker nodes.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The master node consists of a Job Tracker, Task Tracker, NameNode, and DataNode.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] A slave or *worker node* acts as both a DataNode and TaskTracker, though it is possible to have data-only and compute-only worker nodes.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] These are normally used only in nonstandard applications.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Hadoop requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) 1.6 or higher.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The standard startup and shutdown scripts require that Secure Shell (SSH) be set up between nodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] In a larger cluster, HDFS nodes are managed through a dedicated NameNode server to host the file system index, and a secondary NameNode that can generate snapshots of the namenode's memory structures, thereby preventing file-system corruption and loss of data.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Similarly, a standalone JobTracker server can manage job scheduling across nodes.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop MapReduce is used with an alternate file system, the NameNode, secondary NameNode, and DataNode architecture of HDFS are replaced by the file-system-specific equivalents.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The *Hadoop distributed file system* (HDFS) is a distributed, scalable, and portable file system written in Java for the Hadoop framework.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] A Hadoop instance is divided into HDFS and MapReduce.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] HDFS is used for storing the data and MapReduce is used for processing data.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Top three are Master Services/Daemons/Nodes and bottom two are Slave Services.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Master Services can communicate with each other and in the same way Slave services can communicate with each other.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Name Node is a master node and Data node is its corresponding Slave node and can talk with each other.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Hadoop cluster has nominally a single namenode plus a cluster of datanodes, although redundancy options are available for the namenode due to its criticality.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Each datanode serves up blocks of data over the network using a block protocol specific to HDFS.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The file system uses TCP/IP sockets for communication.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Clients use remote procedure calls (RPC) to communicate with each other.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] HDFS stores large files (typically in the range of gigabytes to terabytes) across multiple machines.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] It achieves reliability by replicating the data across multiple hosts, and hence theoretically does not require redundant array of independent disks (RAID) storage on hosts (but to increase input-output (I/O) performance some RAID configurations are still useful).
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] With the default replication value, 3, data is stored on three nodes: two on the same rack, and one on a different rack.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Data nodes can talk to each other to rebalance data, to move copies around, and to keep the replication of data high.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] HDFS is not fully POSIX-compliant, because the requirements for a POSIX file-system differ from the target goals of a Hadoop application.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The trade-off of not having a fully POSIX-compliant file-system is increased performance for data throughput and support for non-POSIX operations such as Append.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] In May 2012, high-availability capabilities were added to HDFS, letting the main metadata server called the NameNode manually fail-over onto a backup.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The project has also started developing automatic fail-overs.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The HDFS file system includes a so-called *secondary namenode*, a misleading term that some might incorrectly interpret as a backup namenode when the primary namenode goes offline.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] In fact, the secondary namenode regularly connects with the primary namenode and builds snapshots of the primary namenode's directory information, which the system then saves to local or remote directories.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] These checkpointed images can be used to restart a failed primary namenode without having to replay the entire journal of file-system actions, then to edit the log to create an up-to-date directory structure.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Because the namenode is the single point for storage and management of metadata, it can become a bottleneck for supporting a huge number of files, especially a large number of small files.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] HDFS Federation, a new addition, aims to tackle this problem to a certain extent by allowing multiple namespaces served by separate namenodes.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Moreover, there are some issues in HDFS such as small file issues, scalability problems, Single Point of Failure (SPoF), and bottlenecks in huge metadata requests.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] One advantage of using HDFS is data awareness between the job tracker and task tracker.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The job tracker schedules map or reduce jobs to task trackers with an awareness of the data location.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] For example: if node A contains data (a, b, c) and node X contains data (x, y, z), the job tracker schedules node A to perform map or reduce tasks on (a, b, c) and node X would be scheduled to perform map or reduce tasks on (x, y, z).
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] This reduces the amount of traffic that goes over the network and prevents unnecessary data transfer.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop is used with other file systems, this advantage is not always available.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] This can have a significant impact on job-completion times as demonstrated with data-intensive jobs.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] HDFS was designed for mostly immutable files and may not be suitable for systems requiring concurrent write operations.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] HDFS can be mounted directly with a Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) virtual file system on Linux and some other Unix systems.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] File access can be achieved through the native Java API, the Thrift API (generates a client in a number of languages e.g.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] C++, Java, Python, PHP, Ruby, Erlang, Perl, Haskell, C#, Cocoa, Smalltalk, and OCaml), the command-line interface, the HDFS-UI web application over HTTP, or via 3rd-party network client libraries.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] HDFS is designed for portability across various hardware platforms and for compatibility with a variety of underlying operating systems.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The HDFS design introduces portability limitations that result in some performance bottlenecks, since the Java implementation cannot use features that are exclusive to the platform on which HDFS is running.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Due to its widespread integration into enterprise-level infrastructure, monitoring HDFS performance at scale has become an increasingly important issue.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Monitoring end-to-end performance requires tracking metrics from datanodes, namenodes, and the underlying operating system.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] There are currently several monitoring platforms to track HDFS performance, including Hortonworks, Cloudera, and Datadog.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Hadoop works directly with any distributed file system that can be mounted by the underlying operating system by simply using a `file://` URL; however, this comes at a price – the loss of locality.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] To reduce network traffic, Hadoop needs to know which servers are closest to the data, information that Hadoop-specific file system bridges can provide.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] A number of third-party file system bridges have also been written, none of which are currently in Hadoop distributions.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] However, some commercial distributions of Hadoop ship with an alternative file system as the default – specifically IBM and MapR.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Atop the file systems comes the MapReduce Engine, which consists of one *JobTracker*, to which client applications submit MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The JobTracker pushes work to available *TaskTracker* nodes in the cluster, striving to keep the work as close to the data as possible.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] With a rack-aware file system, the JobTracker knows which node contains the data, and which other machines are nearby.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] If the work cannot be hosted on the actual node where the data resides, priority is given to nodes in the same rack.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] This reduces network traffic on the main backbone network.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] If a TaskTracker fails or times out, that part of the job is rescheduled.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The TaskTracker on each node spawns a separate Java virtual machine (JVM) process to prevent the TaskTracker itself from failing if the running job crashes its JVM.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] A heartbeat is sent from the TaskTracker to the JobTracker every few minutes to check its status.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The Job Tracker and TaskTracker status and information is exposed by Jetty and can be viewed from a web browser.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] If one TaskTracker is very slow, it can delay the entire MapReduce job – especially towards the end, when everything can end up waiting for the slowest task.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] With speculative execution enabled, however, a single task can be executed on multiple slave nodes.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] By default Hadoop uses FIFO scheduling, and optionally 5 scheduling priorities to schedule jobs from a work queue.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] In version 0.19 the job scheduler was refactored out of the JobTracker, while adding the ability to use an alternate scheduler (such as the *Fair scheduler* or the *Capacity scheduler*, described next).
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler was developed by Facebook.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The goal of the fair scheduler is to provide fast response times for small jobs and quality of service (QoS) for production jobs.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler has three basic concepts.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Each pool is assigned a guaranteed minimum share.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] By default, jobs that are uncategorized go into a default pool.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Pools have to specify the minimum number of map slots, reduce slots, as well as a limit on the number of running jobs.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler was developed by Yahoo.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler supports several features that are similar to those of the fair scheduler.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Free resources are allocated to queues beyond their total capacity.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Within a queue, a job with a high level of priority has access to the queue's resources.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] There is no preemption once a job is running.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The biggest difference between Hadoop 1 and Hadoop 2 is the addition of YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator), which replaced the MapReduce engine in the first version of Hadoop.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] YARN strives to allocate resources to various applications effectively.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] It runs two daemons, which take care of two different tasks: the *resource manager*, which does job tracking and resource allocation to applications, the *application master*, which monitors progress of the execution.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] There are important features provided by Hadoop 3.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] For example, while there is one single *namenode* in Hadoop 2, Hadoop 3, enables having multiple name nodes, which solves the single point of failure problem.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] In Hadoop 3, there are containers working in principle of Docker, which reduces time spent on application development.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] One of the biggest changes is that Hadoop 3 decreases storage overhead with erasure coding.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Also, Hadoop 3 permits usage of GPU hardware within the cluster, which is a very substantial benefit to execute deep learning algorithms on a Hadoop cluster.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The HDFS is not restricted to MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] It can be used for other applications, many of which are under development at Apache.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] The list includes the HBase database, the Apache Mahout machine learning system, and the Apache Hive data warehouse.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Theoretically, Hadoop could be used for any workload that is batch-oriented rather than real-time, is very data-intensive, and benefits from parallel processing.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] It can also be used to complement a real-time system, such as lambda architecture, Apache Storm, Flink, and Spark Streaming.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Inc. launched what they claimed was the world's largest Hadoop production application.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Search Webmap is a Hadoop application that runs on a Linux cluster with more than 10,000 cores and produced data that was used in every Yahoo! web search query.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] There are multiple Hadoop clusters at Yahoo! and no HDFS file systems or MapReduce jobs are split across multiple data centers.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Every Hadoop cluster node bootstraps the Linux image, including the Hadoop distribution.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Work that the clusters perform is known to include the index calculations for the Yahoo! search engine.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] In June 2009, Yahoo! made the source code of its Hadoop version available to the open-source community.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] In 2010, Facebook claimed that they had the largest Hadoop cluster in the world with 21 PB of storage.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] In June 2012, they announced the data had grown to 100 PB and later that year they announced that the data was growing by roughly half a PB per day.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] As of 2013, Hadoop adoption had become widespread: more than half of the Fortune 50 companies used Hadoop.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] Influential papers on the birth, growth, and curation of Hadoop and big data processing include: Jeffrey Dean, Sanjay Ghemawat (2004) MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters, Google.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] This paper inspired Doug Cutting to develop an open-source implementation of the Map-Reduce framework.
[src:apache-accumulo/apache-hadoop] He named it Hadoop, after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] It is now used by a number of Google applications, such as Google Analytics, web indexing, MapReduce, which is often used for generating and modifying data stored in Bigtable, Google Maps, Google Books search, "My Search History", Google Earth, Blogger.com, Google Code hosting, YouTube, and Gmail.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] Google's reasons for developing its own database include scalability and better control of performance characteristics.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] Apache HBase and Cassandra are some of the best known open source projects that were modeled after Bigtable.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] Bigtable offers HBase and Cassandra compatible APIs.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] On 6 May 2015, a public version of Bigtable was made available as a part of Google Cloud under the name Cloud Bigtable.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] As of April 2024, Bigtable manages over 10 Exabytes of data and serves more than 7 billion requests per second.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] Since its launch, Google announced a number of updates to Bigtable, including SQL support, incremental materialized views, global secondary indexes and automated scalability.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] Bigtable is one of the prototypical examples of a wide-column store.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] It maps two arbitrary string values (row key and column key) and timestamp (hence three-dimensional mapping) into an associated arbitrary byte array.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] It is not a relational database and can be better defined as a sparse, distributed multi-dimensional sorted map.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] It is built on Colossus (Google File System), Chubby Lock Service, SSTable (log-structured storage like LevelDB) and a few other Google technologies.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] Bigtable is designed to scale into the petabyte range across "hundreds or thousands of machines, and to make it easy to add more machines [to] the system and automatically start taking advantage of those resources without any reconfiguration".
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] For example, Google's copy of the web can be stored in a bigtable where the row key is a domain-reversed URL, and columns describe various properties of a web page, with one particular column holding the page itself.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] The page column can have several timestamped versions describing different copies of the web page timestamped by when they were fetched.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] Each cell of a bigtable can have zero or more timestamped versions of the data.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] Another function of the timestamp is to allow for both versioning and garbage collection of expired data.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] Tables are split into multiple *tablets* – segments of the table are split at certain row keys so that each tablet is a few hundred megabytes or a few gigabytes in size.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] A bigtable is somewhat like a mapreduce worker pool in that thousands to hundreds of thousands of tablet shards may be served by hundreds to thousands of BigTable servers.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] When Table size threaten to grow beyond a specified limit, the tablets may be compressed using the algorithm BMDiff and the Zippy compression algorithm publicly known and open-sourced as Snappy, which is a less space-optimal variation of LZ77 but more efficient in terms of computing time.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] The locations in the GFS of tablets are recorded as database entries in multiple special tablets, which are called "META1" tablets.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] META1 tablets are found by querying the single "META0" tablet, which typically resides on a server of its own since it is often queried by clients as to the location of the "META1" tablet which itself has the answer to the question of where the actual data is located.
[src:apache-accumulo/bigtable] Like GFS's master server, the META0 server is not generally a bottleneck since the processor time and bandwidth necessary to discover and transmit META1 locations is minimal and clients aggressively cache locations to minimize queries.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The design of Apache Accumulo is inspired by Google’s BigTable paper.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Accumulo provides a richer data model than simple key-value stores, but is not a fully relational database.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] All elements of the Key and the Value are represented as byte arrays except for Timestamp, which is a Long.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Accumulo sorts keys by element and lexicographically in ascending order.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Timestamps are sorted in descending order so that later versions of the same Key appear first in a sequential scan.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Tables consist of a set of sorted key-value pairs.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Accumulo is a distributed data storage and retrieval system and as such consists of several architectural components, some of which run on many individual servers.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Much of the work Accumulo does involves maintaining certain properties of the data, such as organization, availability, and integrity, across many commodity-class machines.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] An instance of Accumulo includes many TabletServers, one Garbage Collector process, one Manager server and many Clients.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The TabletServer manages some subset of all the tablets (partitions of tables).
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] TabletServers also perform recovery of a tablet that was previously on a server that failed, reapplying any writes found in the write-ahead log to the tablet.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Accumulo processes will share files stored in HDFS.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Periodically, the Garbage Collector will identify files that are no longer needed by any process, and delete them.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Multiple garbage collectors can be run to provide hot-standby support.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] They will perform leader election among themselves to choose a single active instance.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Accumulo Manager is responsible for detecting and responding to TabletServer failure.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] It tries to balance the load across TabletServer by assigning tablets carefully and instructing TabletServers to unload tablets when necessary.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Manager ensures all tablets are assigned to one TabletServer each, and handles table creation, alteration, and deletion requests from clients.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Manager also coordinates startup, graceful shutdown and recovery of changes in write-ahead logs when Tablet servers fail.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The managers will choose among themselves a single manager, and the others will become backups if the manager should fail.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Accumulo Tracer process supports the distributed timing API provided by Accumulo.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] One to many of these processes can be run on a cluster which will write the timing information to a given Accumulo table for future reference.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] See the tracing documentation for more information.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Accumulo Monitor is a web application that provides a wealth of information about the state of an instance.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Monitor shows graphs and tables which contain information about read/write rates, cache hit/miss rates, and Accumulo table information such as scan rate and active/queued compactions.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Additionally, the Monitor should always be the first point of entry when attempting to debug an Accumulo problem as it will show high-level problems in addition to aggregated errors from all nodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] See the Accumulo monitor documentation for more information.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Multiple Monitors can be run to provide hot-standby support in the face of failure.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Due to the forwarding of logs from remote hosts to the Monitor, only one Monitor process should be active at one time.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Leader election will be performed internally to choose the active Monitor.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Accumulo Compactor process is an optional application that can be used to run compactions outside of the TabletServer.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] One to many Compactors can be run on a cluster and each Compactor process performs one compaction at a time.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Compactor registers its existence in ZooKeeper and communicates with the Compaction Coordinator to retrieve its work and to register the completion status of the compaction.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Compactor process will continue to perform compactions in situations where normal in-TabletServer compactions would fail, such as TabletServer restart and Tablet re-hosting.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Accumulo Compaction Coordinator is an optional application that is required to run compactions outside of the TabletServer.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Coordinator is responsible for communicating with the TabletServers, to identify what external compaction work needs to be done, and the Compactors to assign work, get status updates, and cancel running external compactions.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Coordinators will choose among themselves a single active Coordinator, and the others will become backups if the active Coordinator should fail.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Accumulo Scan Server is an optional application that can be used to run scans on a tablet’s data outside of the Tablet Server.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Many Scan Servers can be run on a cluster and each Scan Server may run one or more scans concurrently (dependent on configuration).
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Scans running in a Scan Server do not have to be concerned about tablet re-hosting or contention with ingest, compactions, and other tablet maintenance activities.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The trade-off when using Scan Server’s is that the tablet hosted within the ScanServer may not contain the exact same data as the corresponding tablet hosted by the Tablet Server.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Scan Server does not have any of the Tablet data that may reside within the in-memory maps and the tablet may reference files that have been compacted as tablet metadata can be cached within the Scan Server (See Scan Server configuration properties).
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Accumulo has a client library that can be used to write applications that write and read data to/from Accumulo.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] See the Accumulo clients documentation for more information.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Accumulo stores data in tables, which are partitioned into tablets.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Tablets are partitioned on row boundaries so that all of the columns and values for a particular row are found together within the same tablet.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The Manager assigns Tablets to one TabletServer at a time.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] This enables row-level transactions to take place without using distributed locking or some other complicated synchronization mechanism.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] As clients insert and query data, and as machines are added and removed from the cluster, the Manager migrates tablets to ensure they remain available and that the ingest and query load is balanced across the cluster.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] When a write arrives at a TabletServer it is written to a Write-Ahead Log and then inserted into a sorted data structure in memory called a MemTable.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] When the MemTable reaches a certain size, the TabletServer writes out the sorted key-value pairs to a file in HDFS called an RFile.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] This process is called a minor compaction.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] A new MemTable is then created and the fact of the compaction is recorded in the Write-Ahead Log.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] When a request to read data arrives at a TabletServer, the TabletServer does a binary search across the MemTable as well as the index blocks associated with each RFile to find the relevant values.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] If clients are performing a scan, several key-value pairs are returned to the client in order from the MemTable and data blocks of RFiles by performing a sorted merge as they are read.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] If caching is enabled for the table, any index or data block is stored in the block cache to speed up future scans.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] RFile (short for Relative Key File) is a file that contains Accumulo’s sorted key-value pairs.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The file is written to HDFS by Tablet Servers during a minor compaction.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] RFiles are organized using the Index Sequential Access Method (ISAM).
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] RFiles consist of data (key/value) block, index blocks (which are used to find data block), and meta blocks (which contain metadata for bloom filters and summary statistics).
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Data in an RFile is separated by locality group.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The diagram below shows the logical view and HDFS file view of an RFile.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] In order to manage the number of files per tablet, periodically the TabletServer performs Major Compactions of files within a tablet, in which some set of RFiles are combined into one file.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The previous files will eventually be removed by the Garbage Collector.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] This also provides an opportunity to permanently remove deleted key-value pairs by omitting key-value pairs suppressed by a delete entry when the new file is created.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] See the compaction documentation for more information.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] When a table is created it has one tablet.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] As the table grows its initial tablet eventually splits into two tablets.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] It’s likely that one of these tablets will migrate to another tablet server.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] As the table continues to grow, its tablets will continue to split and be migrated.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The decision to automatically split a tablet is based on the size of a tablets files.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] The size threshold at which a tablet splits is configurable per table.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] In addition to automatic splitting, a user can manually add split points to a table to create new tablets.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Manually splitting a new table can parallelize reads and writes giving better initial performance without waiting for automatic splitting.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] As data is deleted from a table, tablets may shrink.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Over time this can lead to small or empty tablets.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] To deal with this, the merging of tablets was introduced in Accumulo 1.4.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] If a TabletServer fails, the Manager detects it and automatically reassigns the tablets assigned from the failed server to other servers.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Any key-value pairs that were in memory at the time the TabletServer fails are automatically reapplied from the Write-Ahead Log(WAL) to prevent any loss of data.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] Tablet servers write their WALs directly to HDFS so the logs are available to all tablet servers for recovery.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] To make the recovery process efficient, the updates within a log are grouped by tablet.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] TabletServers can quickly apply the mutations from the sorted logs that are destined for the tablets they have now been assigned.
[src:apache-accumulo/getting-started-design] TabletServer failures are noted on the Manager’s monitor page, accessible via `http://manager-address:9995/monitor`.
[src:apache-accumulo/wide-column-store] A **wide-column store** (or **extensible record store**) is a type of NoSQL database.
[src:apache-accumulo/wide-column-store] It uses tables, rows, and columns, but unlike a relational database, the names and format of the columns can vary from row to row in the same table.
[src:apache-accumulo/wide-column-store] A wide-column store can be interpreted as a two-dimensional key–value store.
[src:apache-accumulo/wide-column-store] Google's Bigtable is one of the prototypical examples of a wide-column store.
[src:apache-accumulo/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores such as Bigtable and Apache Cassandra are not column stores in the original sense of the term, since their two-level structures do not use a columnar data layout.
[src:apache-accumulo/wide-column-store] In genuine column stores, a columnar data layout is adopted such that each column is stored separately on disk.
[src:apache-accumulo/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores do often support the notion of column families that are stored separately.
[src:apache-accumulo/wide-column-store] However, each such column family typically contains multiple columns that are used together, similar to traditional relational database tables.
[src:apache-accumulo/wide-column-store] Within a given column family, all data is stored in a row-by-row fashion, such that the columns for a given row are stored together, rather than each column being stored separately.
[src:apache-accumulo/wide-column-store] Wide-column stores that support column families are also known as *column family databases*.
